Archbishop Desmond Tutu has retired from public life on his 79th birthday. President Obama recognizes Tutu's many accomplishments as a moral leader, champion of justice, and peacemaker. Tutu played a key role in ending apartheid in South Africa and promoting forgiveness and reconciliation in the country. He has also been an advocate for freedom, justice, and the rights of LGBTQ+ individuals worldwide. Additionally, Tutu has been active in fighting against HIV/AIDS. While his retirement is a loss, his example will continue to inspire others. The President wishes Tutu and his family happiness in the future.